{"questionId":"2966622","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider the function <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math>, defined by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ln</mi><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mo> </mo><mi>ln</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mi>S</mi><mi>x</mi></mfrac></mfenced></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>∈</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>.</p>\n<p>A sketch of the graph of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></math> is shown in the following diagram. Point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is the maximum point on this graph.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/25e5399ab1de5378ebe14753949a47e0a97efd82.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Hence show that the maximum product of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>36</mn></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>OR&nbsp;</strong> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>6</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>OR</strong>&nbsp; graph with maximum at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>36</mn><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>36</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <